data.text:
Site: Bloomington, Ind.

Course: IU Golf Course (par 71, 6,942 yards)

Tournament: Northern Intercollegiate (Day 1 of 2)

U-M Standing: Tie-6th Place of 16 Teams (291) after Round 1

Top U-M Individual: David Nichols, tie-7th (70)

Final Round: Sunday, Sept. 29, 8:30 a.m. EST/CDT

Due to a two-hour fog delay this morning, play did not begin until 10 a.m. Teams did not complete 36 holes of play as the tournament was suspended due to darkness at 6:20 p.m. Rounds two and three will be completed Sunday in the same threesomes starting at 8:30 a.m.

Team Standings (After Round 1)

1. Illinois 280 (-4) 2. Minnesota 281 3. Xavier 282 4. Iowa 285 5. Penn State 287 6. MICHIGAN 291 Ohio 291 8. Wisconsin 292 9. Miami (Ohio) 293 Western Kentucky 293 11. Ohio State 294 Michigan State 294 13. Indiana 295 14. Ball State 296 15. Eastern Michigan 298 16. Marshall 299

Top Individuals

1. James Lepp, Illinois 65 2. Jim Fuller, Penn State 66 Mike Tapper, Iowa 66 4. Tim Smith, Xavier 68 5. Jeff Overton, Indiana 69 Simon Nash, Minnesota 69 7. DAVID NICHOLS, U-M 70 Matt Makinson, Xavier 70 Casey Lubahn, Michigan State 70 Brandon Boomsma, Ball State 70 Wilhelm Schauman, Minnesota 70 Jared Topmiller, Western Ky. 70

Other Michigan Scores

T19. Christian Vozza 72 T40. Mark McIntosh 74 T56. Scott Carlton 75 T56. Rob Tighe 75

N O T E S

Junior David Nichols' one-under-par 70 in first round tied his career-best score. His round was highlighted by three birdies and 13 pars. The only other time he fired a 70 was in the first round of the 2001 Kepler Intercollegiate (April 14-15, 2001).

Freshman Christian Vozza is playing in his first collegiate tournament. In his first collegiate round he carded a one-over-par 72. After playing one under par through his first 15 holes, he bogeyed two of his last three holes to finish his round at plus-one.

Senior/junior Scott Carlton is making his first tournament appearance of the year for the Wolverines.

Q U O T E S

Head Coach Andrew Sapp

On the first day of the Northern Intercollegiate ... "We came out and played really well in the first round. The second round we hit some rough spots, but we have three or five holes to go tomorrow morning to finish the second round and then we will try to do our best in the final round. Dave Nichols and Christian Vozza started off well for us. For Christian to come out in his first collegiate round and shoot a 72, that is pretty solid. He has been a definite bright spot. We just need to try and improve and turn some things around and try and gain some momentum heading into our home tournament next weekend."
